				<br>		      
				
				<table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" width="90%" align="center">
				 <tr>
				  <td>
				    <a name="31">&nbsp;</a><br>
				    <div class="NewsHeadline">Raid Etiquette [good form]</div>
				  </td>
				 </tr>
				 <tr>
				  <td>
				    <div class="NewsInfo">
					RAID INFO -
					Saturday, June 23, 2001&nbsp;14:48
					by 
					<a class="NewsLink" href="author_profile.asp?name=suki">suki</a>
					<br>
				    
				    </div>
				  </td>
				 </tr>
				 <tr>
				   <td>
				     <div class="NewsText" align="justify">
				       1.] Proper Etiquette for Raid Followers <br>Proper etiquette for raid followers is for the most part common sense. When used, it can make for a smooth raid. If one is respectful, understanding, patient, and does what is expected of them, it will make the raid leader's job much less stressful.<br>a] Be respectful: Listen to what the raid leader says and follow his/her instructions, live or die, right or wrong. This does not mean that one should follow blindly or not make any suggestions as to a possible better method. What this does mean, is that if a raid leader declines the suggestion or disagrees with your opinion, then don’t argue about it.<br>b] If you feel the need to make a suggestion, voice a complaint, or ask a question regarding the raid for clarification purposes, do it in '/tell' to the raid leader or someone else who may be able to help. Undermining your raid leader over a full-zone chat option does nothing but destroy morale. You have an idea, it may be scathingly brilliant, feel free to ask if they can use it but if they have something else in mind save it for your own raid.<br>c] Be understanding : Raid leaders will make mistakes. There will be disappointments because when one “golden watch of uberness” drops and there are 3-7 people that want it, there is no way a raid leader can please everyone. Raid leaders may not always form the best groups for your xp needs and raid leaders will not always make the best possible decision. And so, if you feel strongly that the leader has made a mistake that he/she is unaware of, discuss it with them in /tells, in a reasonable manner when there is time. No amount of discussion or righteous indignation about a loot decision can reverse it on n/d gear and your C.E.O. does have the final word. If you missed a call for a random, think you had more merit, or really wanted to be in a group with so and so, keep your cool. Discuss it with them in /tell when there is opportunity. If you can’t agree, chalk it up as a learning lesson for the follower and the leader.<br>d] Be patient: Raid leaders are busy in ways you can’t imagine unless you’ve been there. They have to concern themselves with all aspects of the raid. Everything from who is in which group, strategies for a successful run, what to do if things go wrong, etc. All of that rests on the raid leader's shoulders. Organizing these things is not a simple task and is time consuming. Do understand the leader of a raid may not be able to address one's concerns instantaneously; hence the need to be patient. Trust that the raid leader will address one's request when the opportunity to do so arises.<br>e] Do what is expected: Simply put, one should do his/her job. If that job is to heal, then heal. If that job is to /assist then do so, if that job is to gather the forces with ports, then do the ports. High level raiding is class specific in a way single or small group raids are not. Some classes are going to feel the brunt of this [ex. Enchanters] and others are bound to feel underutilized [ex. Necros]. If everyone on the raid does their job as opposed to doing what they would rather do, then everything will go more smoothly. Having an enchanter nuke themselves out of mana before a big pull and having to rez the the necro that has decided to get some solo xp over and over is going to hinder the raid overall.<br><br>2.] Proper Etiquette for Raid Leaders <br>As a raid leader, one must be understanding, open-minded and polite, as prompt as possible, acknowledge the mistakes they make and do what they can to make amends when such things occur and clear about one's objectives.<br>Be understanding, open-minded and polite: things may come up in rl, causing certain people not to be able to do the functions one would wish them to do. Some may not agree with the decisions one makes as a raid leader. Some may need a more in-depth explanation of the sitituation. As a raid leader one should be aware and listen to the troubles people are experiencing, and do so with an open mind. Give suggestions consideration, listen to complaints without getting overly defensive, and repeat instructions if needed so that everyone knows what is expected.<br>Be as prompt as possible : Raid leaders are busy people, that is understood. But a raid leader who is to busy to address situations, can find themselves with an unhappy, disorganized raid group. Often times a simple 'just a sec' is enough to prevent excessive spamming, or full-zone disruptions.<br>As long as people know they are at least being heard by the raid leader, then they are usually content to give him/her enough breathing room to do what needs to be done first. However, each request should receive its due attention as soon as the opportunity arises to do so.<br>Acknowledge one's mistakes and do what is needed to make amends: As a raid leader, one will make mistakes. People will be unhappy about decisions and occasionally, rightly so. If such a situation occurs, it is more beneficial to actually acknowledge that one has made a mistake, apologize for it, and do what can be done to make amends. If, as a raid leader, one has mistakenly awarded an item to someone and finds out later what they've done, a simple apology to the offended party is often enough. A raid leader should try to make amends when possible, by automatically awarding the next one to that person, or possibly awarding another item. <br>Be clear on objectives : Let the raid group know what to expect. Go over the strategy for the raid; chances are their will be some newer raiding people who are not sure what to do or possibly how to go about doing it. If something comes up [i.e. the raid has lost to many clerics, a bad break means a long cr, or a mistake has been made and needs to be corrected] inform the raid group of the decision and be clear about what needs to be done to get everything back up and running. <br>
				     </div>
				   </td>
				 </tr>		 
